Trump and the Economy
New York – Financial markets finally woke up to the fact that Trump is President of the United States.
The world has endured the global most powerful man's unfiltered tweets and public statements for two years now. An obvious question is, what kept things going for so long?
On one hand, investors have, until now, assumed that Trump was all bark and no bite.
As long as he implemented tax cuts, deregulation, and other pro-business and shareholder policies, they were willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many believed that "the grown-ups in the room" would constrain Trump and ensure that government policies stayed on track.
This assumption was more or less borne out during Trump's first year in office, when economic growth and expectations of corporate profit growth — thanks to imminent tax cuts and deregulation — fueled a stellar stock market performance.
In 2017, US stock indices rose by over 20%.
But this changed dramatically in 2018, particularly in the last few months.
Despite a more than 20% increase in corporate profits (thanks to tax cuts), US stocks fluctuated for much of the year and then fell sharply.
Currently, various indices are in correction mode (down 10% from recent highs), with tech-heavy indices like the Nasdaq having fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
While increased market volatility reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging markets, the recent turmoil has been primarily due to Trump.
At the start of this year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, driving up long-term interest rates and pushing an already near-full-employment economy to the brink.
In February, concerns about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve’s target of 2% led to the first risk-off episode of 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other key US trading partners.
Market concerns about the government's protectionist policies have risen and fallen throughout the year but are now reaching new heights.
Recently, the US actions toward China appear to be preparing for a full-fledged trade, economic, and geo-political cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies could lead to stagflation (weaker growth and higher inflation).
Af ter all, Trump has prepared to limit foreign direct investment inflows and implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will drag on labor supply growth as the population ages and skills mismatch becomes more severe.
In addition, the Trump administration has yet to propose an infrastructure program that could stimulate private-sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy.
In his tweets and elsewhere, Trump has continually criticized business hiring, production, investment, and pricing practices, especially those of tech companies, which already face widespread opposition and intensifying competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets have also felt the impact of US policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening have pushed up both short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
The result has been capital flight and rising values of dollar-denominated debt for emerging economies.
Severely export-dependent emerging economies have suffered from falling commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade connections to China have felt the effects of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policies have created volatility.
US sanctions on Iran pushed up oil prices, but after that, the US government threatened Saudi Arabia to increase oil production by revoking exemptions, leading to a sharp drop in oil prices.
While American consumers benefited from low oil prices, oil company stocks couldn't withstand the pressure.
Moreover, excessive price volatility is detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hinders wise investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, it is now clear that almost all the benefits from last year's tax cuts seem to have gone to the corporate sector rather than to families in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This means that household consumption may soon slow down, further affecting the economy.
However, the recent plunge in US and global stock markets is primarily due to Trump himself and his actions.
Worse than the looming risk of a full-scale trade war with China (despite his recent "truce" with Chinese President Xi Jinping), is Trump's open criticism of the Fed. His attacks began in the spring of 2018 when US economic growth was above 4%.
Because of these earlier attacks, the markets became unnerved when the Fed, correctly, raised rates this month and signaled slower hikes in 2019.
It is more likely that the Fed's relatively hawkish stance is a reaction to Trump's criticisms.
Facing hostile tweets from a hostile president, Jerome Powell, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, needs to signal that the central bank remains politically independent.
But then, because Congress refused to fund his useless border wall with Mexico, Trump decided to let the federal government partially shut down.
This put the market into near panic mode, and with the government shutdown, reports quickly emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell — which could turn a correction into a crash.
Just before Christmas, Steven Mnuchin, the US treasury secretary, was forced to issue a public statement calming the market.
He declared that Trump had no intention of firing Powell, and that the US fiscal situation was good, which actually highlighted the question of whether things really were good.
And government changes that do not necessarily affect economic decisions have recently caused market concerns.
White House chief of staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are set to leave, leaving the Trump cabinet without any sound minds.
The remaining members will all be economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks who follow Trump's lead.
The possibility of a comprehensive geo-political confrontation with China remains.
A new cold war could lead to de-globalization, disrupting global supply chains, and the tech industry will be hit hardest, as evidenced by the recent cases against ZTE and Huawei.
Meanwhile, Trump appears determined to destabilize EU and NATO cohesion while Europe's economy and politics are already in flux.
The special counsel investigation into Trump's 2016 campaign ties to Russia hangs like a sword of Damocles over his presidency.
Trump is now the financial markets' Dr. Strangelove.
Like the paranoid megalomaniac in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is mired in a mutually assured economic destruction from which he cannot extricate himself.
Markets are now seeing the danger, with the risk of another financial crisis and global recession on the rise.
